<subSubSection pageId="529" pageNumber="530" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="529" pageNumber="530">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Dyke" authorityYear="1926" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Pterostichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="529" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beyeri">Pterostichus beyeri</taxonomicName>
Van Dyke, 1926a: 71. Type locality: &quot;Bitter Root Mountains, Montana&quot; (original citation). Holotype (♂) in CAS [# 1823]. Etymology. The specific name honors Gustav Beyer [1840-1924], a fur manufacturer but also a naturalist and insect collector. Beyer was a founding member of the New York Entomological Society.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="529" pageNumber="530">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hatch" authorityYear="1936" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Pterostichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="529" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="idahoensis">Pterostichus idahoensis</taxonomicName>
Hatch, 1936: 706. Type locality: &quot;Pierce [Clearwater County], Id[aho]&quot; (original citation). Holotype (♀) in USNM. Synonymy established by Hatch (1953: 112).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="529" pageNumber="530" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="529" pageNumber="530">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="529" pageNumber="530">This species is known from a few specimens collected in northern Idaho and along the western edge of Montana (Hacker 1968: 36; see Will and Gill 2008: Fig. 15).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
